Refactor to be more git-aware

imagebuilder previously checked if the image existed on
the registry before building it. While technically cleaner,
this caused the following problems:

- Building in CI for PRs becomes impossible when using private
  registries
- It doesn't actually make the code that much cleaner
- Local builds are just as easy to trigger when using --commit-range,
  with official/master...HEAD (or origin/master...HEAD) to build
  changed files.
- It made testing more complicated

Instead, we now reuse the same logic from chartpress,
and use git commits to figure out when to build an image.

Add --check-registry option to image building

This checks if the image we are going to build is already
present in the remote registry, and if not, forces a rebuild.

This is a more reliable way to force rebuilds during deployments,
since COMMIT_RANGE might not work for a variety of reasons:

1. Previous deployment failed (even though PR succeeded). This would
   mean there would be no rebuild / push in new deployment, and
   helm deploy would fail since it can't find the image we are
   looking for
2. CircleCI is terrible at giving us COMMIT_RANGE, and any workarounds
   we bring up are messy. It doesn't give us the merged PR's number
   reliably, causing many problems.

Ensure `credHelpers` key exists in ~/.docker/config.json

`hubploy build` authenticates to AWS ECR by adding an `credHelpers`
entry pointing to [ecr-login](1) to ~/.docker/config.json.
If a ~/.docker/config.json file already exists but does not
have a `credHelpers` entry, a KeyError was raised and hubploy
failed.

[1]: https://github.com/awslabs/amazon-ecr-credential-helper

Use a temporary KUBECONFIG file for all cluster auth

The current context for kubectl should ideally not change
when running hubploy. Almost all the tools used for fetching
cluster auth info write credentials to file specified in
KUBECONFIG. Temporarily setting that var for the course of
our deployment works great - helm can read from it too!
Remove unused and wrong image-builder docs

Support --set-string and avoid numerical image tag bug

When using the helm CLI and `--set`, it cannot know when it receives
it's argument if the value was meant as a string or as an integer if it
receives the string `12334567`.

The helm CLI has opted to have the `--set-string` flag to enforce a set
value to be a string value even if it looks numerical. We should ensure
that we always set image tags and names as strings, or we run into
issues like
https://github.com/earthlab/hub-ops/pull/199#issuecomment-619099629.

Add option to specify which images to build explicitly

When building multiple images, you might want to do those
steps separately. This is particularly important on GitHub
actions, where the GitHub hosted runners only have 14G of
disk space. You can clean out docker image cache between
runs to make enough space.

Add support for a 'secrets' submodule

Often, you want to keep all your secrets in an entirely
different git repo than your public deployment repo. With
this change, the 'secret' repo can be referenced here as a
submodule in the path 'secrets'. The same config paths
(deployments/<deployment>/(config|secret)/(common|staging|prod).yaml)
works inside the secrets repo too.
